SUBJECT: One City. One World. One Game - A Legacy Project
CONTENT: Date: January 31, 2026 ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† To: Google Arts & Culture / Google Maps Platform Partnerships Subject: LETTER OF INTENT: Google x ArtTechVibe ‚Äì Geospatial AR Legacy Project  Dear Justin  We are pleased to submit this Letter of Intent to partner with Google on the "One City. One Game. One World." activation, an ArtTechVibe initiative designed for the 2026 World Cup in Seattle.  The Project: Our "Unity Loop" uses high-vibrancy physical murals to foster community resilience and equality. We aim to use Google‚Äôs ARCore Geospatial API and Geospatial Creator to anchor digital stories to Seattle‚Äôs "King Street Crossing," allowing fans to experience immersive 3D content through their mobile browsers with sub-meter accuracy.  The Partnership Opportunity: We propose ArtTechVibe as a "Cultural Landmark" pilot to:  Automate World-Scale AR: Utilize Google‚Äôs Photorealistic 3D Tiles and Rooftop Anchors to make our murals permanent digital icons on Google Maps and Street View.  Cultural Preservation: Partner with Google Arts & Culture to archive Leslie Casta√±eda‚Äôs mural series as a permanent digital collection, ensuring the project‚Äôs "Art with a Heart" mission lives on after the tournament.  Inclusive Technology: Demonstrate a "no-app-download" AR experience that prioritizes digital accessibility for global visitors.  Commitment to Success: We have already secured a $32,575 community match in professional services and materials. We are looking for Google to provide the technical infrastructure and automation support to scale this project for the millions of fans expected in Seattle.  We look forward to discussing how we can integrate our site-specific AR models with Google‚Äôs latest geospatial innovations.  Best regards, Leslie Casta√±eda Founder ArtTechVibe

Hey Elizabeth. I was just reading James Hunter's book on Democracy and Solidarity today. Towards the end, he has no policy prescriptions, but he does have a set of principles he hopes can help us transform our democracy. Toughest among these, he estimates, is leadership. Here's what he says about it:  "This kind of leadership would have to be prepared to be ignored, then dismissed as naive, and then despised by the main partisans who would ultimately see its exemplars as a threat to their interests. Such is the progression in any important paradigm shift. Invariably, reputation and livelihood would be at risk, but without putting such things at risk, leadership would lack credibility or authority."  I'm so sorry to hear you're going through something similar at Genentech as what I went through a few months ago at Google. It rips your heart out. But, I think for those of us going through it, it's preparing us for leadership roles in helping our country find its way out of this hole. Experiences like this, I believe, are a prerequisite for the leaders to come. It humbles you in ways that are very necessary.  Yes, happy to connect. Here's a link to my calendar. You and son should definitely come camping with us! We put a lot of thought into ensuring that we create a culturally space safe for BIPOC families, and we also want to create bridges across class/culture/race. We've had several white families join us and fit right in, and knowing you and your values, I think you'd fit right in too. It's been a beautiful thing to watch folks connect in ways that are very hard outside of these kinds of intentional, public spaces.  And I totally hear you on the camping hang ups. As you can imagine, our families have all kinds of reasons why they've never camped or only done it once and never again. We often camp in campgrounds with showers, and we always bring our own shower with an on-demand hot water heater so that folks who want to shower every day can do that (and there are always a few!). We also have folks who bring white noise machines into their tents and any number of other sleep aids (heated blankets, etc.) to ensure they get a good night's rest. You'd be in good company feeling hesitant about whether you can actually be comfortable camping.¬†We call what we do DIY glamping. We're working hard to make it work for everyone.  We're definitely in a relationship building phase with folks who want to come on this journey with us, and we're so grateful for any introductions to people who are interested in learning more and getting to know us. You know I know how funders/donors can be, so totally defer to you on how best to position it. Happy to wait until you get a signal there's interest, but also happy to make the time to share more with you if you want. Totally up to you.  Thanks again Lara!

(am too light a sleeper to sleep well outside, can‚Äôt wake up well without a shower or at least a dip in a lake, etc) and also don‚Äôt have the gear - yet as a mom now, I know how much my kiddo (who is five and a fabulous hiking companion) would love camping so feel I need to get over my own feelings and just do it with him! Thus your posts inspire me to think about trying it. (And I‚Äôll note that I would love to come on one of your trips but as a white person don‚Äôt want to encroach on such an important space of safety for other participants.) I do have a client with a focus on access to the outdoors for kids from under-represented backgrounds, and at MCF we have a few other clients with similar focuses; plus I just got connected to a philanthropic advisor at the east bay community foundation who has a client with this interest and specifically focused on the east bay. Hi Justin,  Hope all is well with you!  I'd like to personally invite you to join us for the Connected for Kids Launch Webinar on Thursday, November 13 at 1:00 pm ET.  Connected for Kids is a new national effort to align research, policy, and practice so that children experience connection, belonging, and opportunity wherever they live and learn. Led by Child Trends and the Thrive Center at Georgetown University, the initiative brings together leaders across education, health, youth development, mental health, and community development to co-create a shared roadmap for flourishing in the elementary years.  These ‚Äúmissing middle‚Äù years are a turning point. They carry early childhood investments forward and keep kids on track into adolescence, at a time when AI, social media, and isolation are reshaping childhood. The silos that fragment our work are not our fault, but we have the collective power to break them down. We can do more by doing it together. Connected for Kids is a roadmap to get there.  This webinar marks the beginning of a national effort to connect the dots between what we know from science and what children experience every day. You‚Äôll hear from national leaders about how we can build a more connected, coordinated approach to help every child grow up healthy, supported, and full of possibility. Hi Phil, good to be connected. Thanks for sharing more about¬†Connected for Kids. I'm heads down building Kindora every day as our CEO and CTO, so am stretched thinner than I've ever been (plus I'm raising four girls!), but if there are ways I can be helpful, let me know.

Hi Justin,  Thanks for connecting with me. I really appreciate the way you‚Äôre reimagining what technology and philanthropy can do together‚Äîbuilding tools that actually serve the people doing the work on the ground.  I‚Äôd love to get you up to speed on a project I‚Äôm leading called Connected for Kids, in partnership with Child Trends and the Georgetown Thrive Center. We‚Äôre building a shared framework for flourishing that aligns policy, programs, and philanthropy around what kids truly need‚Äîbelonging, curiosity, and connection.  Right now, the national conversation about children is split in two. One is about academics and test scores. The other is about sadness, loneliness, and mental health. But it really needs to be one conversation. As Jonathan Haidt notes in The Anxious Generation, disconnection erodes both wellbeing and learning‚Äîso we can‚Äôt separate them.  Our focus is the elementary years‚Äîthe ‚Äúmissing middle‚Äù that carries early childhood investments forward and keeps kids on track into adolescence and beyond. The big swing is applying research to policy so everyone can work from the same playbook. We‚Äôre trying to build a movement‚Äîuniting schools, communities, and funders behind a shared North Star for what childhood should be.  We‚Äôd be honored if you followed our Connected for Kids newsletter: https://www.linkedin.com/newsletters/connected-for-kids-7360083728108249088/  And if you‚Äôre open, here‚Äôs my Calendly to find a time: https://calendly.com/philipsteigman  In partnership, Phil

CONTENT: Hi Justin,  I recently saw a great post recently about a session you did with my friend Gayle Roberts for AIxImpact, and was really impressed with your work. But I do believe that someday (not during this administration) we'll see regulations on these foundation > DAF (warehouse-to-warehouse) transfers.¬†  Interestingly, keeping grant making opaque may be good for now, as we see the gov't stopping grants to race-based work, i.e. DEI training, etc..¬†  I'm just waiting for the hammer to fall on the private sector (beyond DEI rollbacks, I mean).

Thank you so much for replying, appreciate that very much.¬†  So, you're talking about this Google foundation that was shuttered:¬†https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/201548253  So, no more separate legal c3 entity to handle Google's philanthropy.   My only fear when commingling philanthropy with business is that grant making may decrease. Probably irrational on my part as I know Google.org is the gold standard....but, other companies.¬†  But for transparency, and for those of us, like me, that like to keep an eye on things via 990s, you can't see any more grant making details.¬†  Again, thank you so much for replying to my questions.¬†  Matt

Hi Matt, sometimes they are separate, but increasingly less so. Some companies have foundations that are separate from the company, but even then, many of those foundations are staffed by company employees. Google used to have a foundation and ran it this way until they shut down the foundation around 2017. Now most giving comes straight from the company. In practice, there is often little separation between the philanthropy and the business functions in many companies.   Happy to share more if any of that is confusing.

Hey Kendra, hope you're well.  I was looking at your work at Duolingo,¬† particularly Early Learners First. Having spent a decade directing corporate philanthropy at Google, I admire how you're investing in system-level change rather than just individual support. The business stabilization approach (strengthening childcare infrastructure rather than band-aid solutions) reflects the kind of strategic social impact work that's rare in corporate settings.  Since leaving Google last year, my co-founder and wife Sally and I started Outdoorithm Collective, working to combat isolation by making camping accessible to families historically underrepresented outdoors‚Äîparticularly Black and Brown urban families. We've built a platform to help people plan outdoor adventures and are seeing solid engagement, but we know technology alone won't close the confidence gap.  We've been studying Duolingo's approach to turning complex skills into achievable actions while centering joy and inclusion. Would you be open to a brief conversation? Emphasize the ‚Äútrust network‚Äù strategy ‚Äî why SafeSign will be seen as safe enough to upload confidential leases.  Impact metrics.  Funders will want to see short- and long-term KPIs: e.g., leases analyzed, violations corrected, rent savings achieved, collective negotiations launched, or SB 1103 enforcement cases supported.  Suggest a one-page logic model or mini-dashboard visualization.  Competitive differentiation.  The ‚ÄúIncumbent‚Äôs Dilemma‚Äù section is strong; add a single table comparing SafeSign vs. CoStar, CompStak, and legal aid tools (e.g., JusticeText, LegalRobot). That will make the unfair advantage more tangible.  Technical credibility.  A brief mention of how AI parses leases (LLMs + supervised training + validation from attorneys) could reassure non-technical readers.  Add a note on data privacy and anonymization protocols ‚Äî it‚Äôs both a risk and a selling point.  Tone & pacing.  The writing occasionally veers from brief to essay (e.g., long sentences in ‚ÄúThe Hard Truth‚Äù). Tightening those paragraphs would give it more punch.  Consider a one-paragraph summary upfront that distills what SafeSign does, who it serves, and why now, before diving into narrative detail.  Visuals: Add a concept flow diagram showing the data flywheel or MVP feature stack.  Advisory bench: A short list of committed or target advisors (legal, AI, small business) would increase credibility.  Pilot partners: Listing 2‚Äì3 named organizations (e.g., Black Cultural Zone, Renaissance Entrepreneurship Center) strengthens early traction.

Hey Cordell, hope you and your family are well! I still think back to and reference your¬†2023 Socrates seminar "Can We Imagine a Future Beyond Race?" - particularly the idea of retiring from certain aspects of being Black that are entangled in struggles for power and ego. I appreciate that you created the space for that dialogue.  I'm now building something with my wife that explores broader themes of belonging and healing for folks of color. At Outdoorithm Collective, we create what you might call "bridging spaces" through wilderness camping - 72-hour experiences where urban families across race and class lines share tent stakes and camp stoves. When people have a tendency to believe our common societal structure has been created out of some natural order, the wilderness reminds us that the imagined thing is bound to feel uncomfortable.  We just completed our 10th trip this past weekend and are launching nationally. Families are already traveling from Cleveland, Dallas, and DC to join us for our trips in California. I've been using my engineering degree and Google experience to build technology to maintain these connections between trips and facilitate self-organizing.  Given your work on belonging and the Festival of the Diaspora's focus on fostering inclusive societies, I wonder if there are potential synergies to explore - whether through your network, upcoming summits, or connections to funders/communities passionate about innovative approaches to social cohesion.  Let me know if that sparks a thought for you that you'd be down to explore more!  Justin

CONTENT: Hi Justin! Short question‚Ä¶  Are you open to explore what a well-integrated offshore team could actually take off your plate?  I'm pretty sure you already felt this...  You land a new client. The team‚Äôs excited. The scope looks great on paper.  But then the ‚Äúreal work‚Äù begins: Tier-1 tickets, client onboarding, 3AM pings, compliance checklists‚Ä¶  ‚Ä¶and before long, your senior engineers are buried in things they were never hired to do.  That‚Äôs the hidden tax of growth in IT and cybersecurity. The more clients you win, the more your best people are pulled into work that kills margins and morale.  At All Sourcing Group, we help IT firms quietly build a trusted offshore bench, so routine support, monitoring, and admin stop slowing your team down.  We‚Äôve helped dozens of IT firms, free up senior engineering time and scale 24/7 coverage,  who now run leaner ops, faster support, and tighter SLAs‚Ä¶ without over-hiring or burning out core staff. CONTENT: Hi Justin,   I work with Heidrick & Struggles ‚Äì we‚Äôre an executive recruiting firm partnering with Genesys Works [https://genesysworks.org/] on the search for their next CEO. I wanted to reach out to see if you might have ideas, recommendations, or potential interest in the role.   Genesys Works [https://genesysworks.org/] is a nationally federated nonprofit that partners with corporations and businesses in 8 cities to provide meaningful internship opportunities to high school students in underserved communities. In addition, Genesys Works provides skills training, career coaching, networking, and community-building opportunities to support students in their early career journey.   At this time, Genesys Works seeks a CEO who can help drive its strategic priorities around growing in new and existing sites, codifying its best practices, and driving stronger outcomes for its students. This next leader will guide the organization in a forward-looking, innovative direction regarding the future of skills development and early career growth. They will lead and strategically align a federated organization to meet ambitious growth goals, ensuring strong operational scaling and revenue generation strategies with corporate partners and donors.  They will be the face of the organization, raising its national visibility and building out key relationships that help the organization grow its influence and partnerships.   I‚Äôve attached a position specification with additional information. If you‚Äôre interested, I‚Äôd love to connect and share more. Let me know if there are a few windows that work to connect, and I can coordinate a time to connect.   Best,  Alissa Fernandez (alfernandez@heidrick.com) Engagement Manager at Heidrick & Struggles

Folks who camp on public land are pretty much an even split between urban/rural/suburban. Half of folks out there make less than $50K a year, but there are a solid number of higher income folks too. It's predominantly white overall (80%), but new campers are 40% people of color. It's one of the few spaces left where there are genuine opportunities for building civic health across communities where folks can interact on equal footing and it hasn't been overly privatized. There also several collective impact projects considering coming to the Bay Area around this. One led by Children and Nature Network, another led by the Outdoor Foundation. I'm wondering whether we think we might be able to get corporate support from among our peers for something like that. I'm already working on the community foundations.  Anyways, lots of wonderings and dreaming. Would be fun to bounce some of it off you and hear what you think.

Hi Carrie!  I love this question‚Äîit‚Äôs exactly what Outdoorithm is designed to answer! Your query is the perfect test for our campsite matching tool, which we‚Äôre still developing. Since the UI is not ready yet, I ran your question myself and here‚Äôs the raw output. I‚Äôve camped at Wrights Lake and Gerle Creek, and they‚Äôre fantastic. I haven‚Äôt camped at Utica Reservoir, but I‚Äôve hiked near it and can confirm it‚Äôs pristine.  Wrights Lake Campground: This might be perfect for you! It‚Äôs tucked near the lake in the Sierra Nevadas, with peaceful non-motorized water for kayaking or fishing and forested hiking trails that lead into the Desolation Wilderness. If you‚Äôre up for it, you could even snag a backpacking permit for a night in the wilderness. It‚Äôs quiet, scenic, and offers some private spots‚Äîsite 8 is the top pick (spacious and shaded by the lake), with 5 and 43 as other great options. Sites here offer some privacy but not as much as others.  Utica Reservoir: If you‚Äôre looking for a quiet, off-the-grid camping experience, Utica is a gem. It‚Äôs nestled in the Stanislaus National Forest, surrounded by granite outcrops, pine trees, and calm waters perfect for kayaking, fishing, or swimming. Campsites are all first-come, first-served, so plan to head out early‚Äîand your 4x4 will be essential for navigating the rough road. It‚Äôs a rugged, no-hookups kind of spot, but the views and tranquility make it unforgettable.  Gerle Creek Campground: Located in Eldorado National Forest, this spot is super peaceful, right on the banks of the Gerle Creek reservoir. There are no speedboats or jet skis‚Äîjust calm water for swimming or canoeing. The sites are private, with great forested hiking trails nearby. It‚Äôs rustic (no showers or potable water), but since you‚Äôre self-sufficient, it‚Äôs a great fit! Best sites are 32 (most private, spacious, lake access) and 31 (lakefront, shaded), with 40 as a quiet, wooded retreat.  I‚Äôd also recommend checking out map.outdoorithm.com‚Äîfilter for ‚ÄúTop-Rated‚Äù or ‚ÄúRecommended‚Äù and explore the Sierras. The whole area north of Lake Tahoe is dotted with nice off the grid spots. You can see historical weather data for summer to help plan your trip.   If you‚Äôre aiming for Wrights Lake or Gerle Creek, book now for July. Otherwise, Utica (or similar first-come, first-served spots) is a great alternative. I also use Wandering Labs to snag reservations from cancellations.  Let me know how this works for you, and feel free to share any feedback on the map or tools‚Äîwe‚Äôre launching a big update soon!  Justin

As we approach some well-earned downtime, reflect on 2024, and start dreaming about the change we want to make in 2025, I just want to take a moment to express my gratitude for this incredible Bay Area impact community.  Last month marked my 20th anniversary of moving to San Francisco. I‚Äôll never forget the joy and awe I felt on move-in day, November 15, 2004, settling into my very own one-bedroom apartment in Cole Valley with a backyard ($900 per month rent!) and beginning my career in the nonprofit sector. From that moment, I knew this place was home. Twenty years later, the Bay Area is still my home, and I‚Äôm so thankful for the colleagues-turned-friends and this vibrant network that continues to inspire me every day.  A special thanks to Katherine Woo for joining forces to kick off this gathering two years ago - a space where impact-driven folks can come together every other month with no agenda, no pressure, just connection. The six gatherings we had this year brought me so much joy, and I‚Äôm already looking forward to what‚Äôs ahead in 2025.  To kick off the new year, I hope this makes our SF folks especially happy - we‚Äôre starting in the city! Save the date:  What: Social Impact Gathering When: Wednesday, February 5, 2025, 3:00 - 8:00 PM Where: Southern Pacific Brewing, 620 Treat Ave, San Francisco  Wishing you all joyful, restful moments amidst the holiday chaos! Can‚Äôt wait to see you in the new year.  Warmly, K  --------------------------------------  Background: For anyone new to this group, in 2023 we initiated this gathering to connect social impact enthusiasts in Marin. From there, it has grown to encompass the whole Bay Area (as well as social impact + sustainability friends who are in from out of town too!). We have friends here from the corporate social impact sector, sustainability/climate sector, nonprofit sector, and mission-driven intermediaries as well. Some of our regulars include friends from Salesforce, Airbnb, Kiva, IDEO.org, and many other great orgs.   Details: Typically we meet at The Junction in Mill Valley which has a tasty + simple menu of pizzas and salads, and we pull a few picnic tables together and people order and share and catch up. Hey Bry, always good to hear from you. We're definitely seeing a renewed appetite internally for justice oriented work. Yesterday we announced a $1M grant to Morehouse (https://www.msm.edu/RSSFeedArticles/2020/May/satcher-institute-receives-1m-google-grant-covid-19.php) alongside immediate relief support through Live Free's Masks for the People campaign and Hispanic Federation's COVID relief fund. Today we're standing up an internal giving campaign focused more directly on the violence we're seeing. The four orgs (all existing Google.org grantees) are the following:  Center for Policing Equity: CPE is a team of research scientists, race and equity experts, data virtuosos, and community trainers that partner with police departments to diagnose the roots of disparate policing in order to eliminate them.   Live Free: Live Free works to address gun violence and mass incarceration. They have also started a Masks for the People campaign to transform their national network of community organizers in the most marginalized black communities across the country and created their own PPE supply chain to distribute masks and sanitizer to essential workers.  Equal Justice Initiative: EJI challenges racial and economic injustice, provides legal representation to prisoners who may have been wrongly convicted of crimes, and protects basic human rights for the most vulnerable people in American society. Founded by celebrated civil rights lawyer Bryan Stevenson, EJI works to end mass incarceration and excessive punishment, stop the prosecution of children as adults, aid the mentally ill in the criminal justice system, confront the history of racial inequality in America and provide free legal services to the poor, incarcerated and condemned.  NAACP: The NAACP's #WeAreDoneDying campaign has been established to address the disproportionate impact of COVID-19 on the Black community and combat the consistent mistreatment of African American communities long before there was a pandemic.

Hi Justin‚ÄîCongratulations on your new gig with Coding Temples! I‚Äôve been meaning to write to you about income-sharing agreements. I know that the CFPB and 11 states filed lawsuits against the origination and collection of ISAs in 2023 (https://www.consumerfinancemonitor.com/2023/07/18/cfpb-and-11-states-file-lawsuit-against-companies-engaged-in-origination-and-collection-of-income-share-agreements/), and I know some asset managers have pulled back ISA strategies. An alternative way to structure it might be to create an income-based student debt payment structure. That way, you could forgive the debt if necessary. You would need to work with a lawyer to determine any legal risks on CT‚Äôs side and the tax implications for the learner if you discharge the debt. SUBJECT: Bridging Financial Barriers to Tech Careers in Chicago
CONTENT: Hi LaKendric,  I'm reaching out in my capacity as the Chief Impact Officer at the Coding Temple Foundation.  My personal journey in workforce development spans from leading programs at Year Up to most recently directing over half a billion dollars in philanthropy at Google.org, including the creation of the $100M Google Career Certificates Fund. This work has shown me repeatedly: when we remove financial obstacles, talented people thrive.  We've identified an important opportunity at Coding Temple: while 9,000+ applicants annually demonstrate the technical aptitude to succeed in our program, 87% cannot enroll due to financial constraints, with 78% of these qualified non-enrolling applicants coming from underrepresented backgrounds. Here in Chicago specifically, we're seeing these same patterns, with talented individuals unable to access transformative education despite having the skills to succeed.  I'm particularly impressed by Boeing's commitment to "inspiring tomorrow's innovators" through your community investment approach. The technical skills we teach directly complement the STEM talent pipeline that companies like Boeing have been cultivating in Chicago for years.  Would you be open to a brief conversation about how Boeing and Coding Temple Foundation could partner to expand access to transformative tech education for Chicago residents? I'd welcome the chance to share more about our approach, hear more about your workforce development priorities within Boeing's community strategy, and explore where our goals might align.  Looking forward to connecting,  Justin

CONVERSATION TITLE: Transforming Mental Healthcare with Kuddo (Angel Round)
SUBJECT: Transforming Mental Healthcare with Kuddo (Angel Round)
CONTENT: Hi Justin,  I am building Kuddo, an AI-powered platform for eating disorder treatment fidelity that helps organizations, clinicians, and parents ensure high-quality mental healthcare at scale.  Mental healthcare is facing a crisis, 80% of youth do not receive adequate care, and even when they do, treatment fidelity and clinician burnout remain major challenges.  Kuddo addresses these challenges by offering real-time fidelity assessment for organizations, AI-driven session structuring to enhance clinician efficiency, and 24/7 AI-powered support with real-time interventions and gamified engagement to improve patient and parent adherence.  Kuddo‚Äôs Key Highlights and Developments: * Raising $1M SAFE round ($250K filled) * $377K ACV signed in LOIs for pilot programs with 3 private therapy practices * Founding team from Stanford Medicine (CCO), Harvard Medical School + Mass General Hospital (CTO), Carnegie Mellon (CEO) * Advisors from Weill Cornell, New York Presbyterian Hospital, Cerebral  My co-founders and I are on a mission to revolutionize mental health care. We are bringing together like-minded individuals who share our vision and are interested in participating in our angel funding round.  I would love to discuss how we can work together to bring this vision to life. I have attached our pitch deck [https://hubs.ly/Q033lC-F0] for more details, and you can complete this short form [https://share.hsforms.com/1Y8NUDBjgTD6b0WeygXrfvAnjiff] to express your interest.  Looking forward to your thoughts!  Best Regards, Wenyi Zhu  Wenyi Zhu CEO @ Kuddo | AI Companion for Eating Disorder Treatment Fidelity  Scaling Quality, Not Just Access

Hey Sean,  Love that we both have four kids‚Äîour girls are 15, 13, 11, and 3, and we totally embrace the chaos too! So great to hear your family loves camping. It's set among beautiful old-growth redwoods and along the Eel River‚Äîshould be an amazing gathering. Also, if it‚Äôs helpful for your planning, we created a sister tech platform, www.outdoorithm.com, designed to simplify the logistics of camping. There's an interactive campground map (map.outdoorithm.com) featuring sentiment analysis of public campgrounds, historical weather data, forecasts, and soon some new AI-powered tools we're excited to launch. Our vision is that revenue from the tech platform could someday sustainably fund Outdoorithm Collective.  Looking forward to connecting more!  Warmly,  Justin

SUBJECT: Exploring Shared Ground Around Belonging, Spiritiuality and Place
CONTENT: Hi Jason,  I hope you're well. I'm reaching out as I noticed we have several mutual connections, including Michelle Jawando and Adam Taylor. I recently transitioned out of Google after nearly a decade leading their largest philanthropy team, and I'm now co-founding Outdoorithm Collective with my wife, Sally, an ordained minister with an MDiv from Gordon-Conwell‚Äîshe even took some classes at Harvard Divinity School around the same time you were there. (I was across the street completing my MBA/MPA at Harvard.)  Outdoorithm Collective is a nonprofit we've created to connect urban families, particularly families of color like our own here in Oakland, with immersive outdoor experiences. While camping and nature are at our core, our deeper aim is fostering community, inner wellbeing, and belonging. We see parks and outdoor spaces as powerful settings for bridging divides‚Äîplaces where families from different backgrounds can organically build trust, mutual respect, and a stronger sense of shared humanity through simple yet profound shared experiences.  Given your leadership at the intersection of faith, bridging, and belonging‚Äîand our own experiences wrestling with these issues through deep bridging work with colleagues like john powell‚ÄîI would love the opportunity to learn more about your work and approach at the Freedom Together Foundation. It would be great to compare notes, hear your advice, and explore how your insights might shape our thinking and impact.  Would you be open to a brief conversation sometime soon?  Warm regards,  Justin

Hi Justin,  Yeah, I‚Äôd say the area that feels most lacking is the career support and follow-through, but not in an accusatory way. It‚Äôs more like‚Ä¶ I‚Äôve been sitting with this question of ‚ÄúWhy do I still feel so lost?‚Äù  Part of me keeps thinking maybe I just need to try harder. But even when I do, that lost feeling doesn‚Äôt really go away. And I‚Äôve noticed I‚Äôm not alone ‚Äî a lot of the people I‚Äôve connected with from the software engineering track seem to be in the same boat. It feels like there‚Äôs plenty of opportunity to practice job searching, but not much traction when it comes to real interviews.  I imagined when signing up a defined path ‚Äî like a curated job board with partner companies, or active recruiting efforts. Maybe that‚Äôs not a thing anymore? I don‚Äôt know. What I do know is that while I love the alumni community ‚Äî because they‚Äôre just like me in many ways ‚Äî we‚Äôre all kind of flopping around in what feels like a drying-up lakebed. And I‚Äôm sitting here thinking: we need some rain.  I'm trying to use my experience to refine what types of roles I should actually be going for, and ideally tailor my resume for each ‚Äî but there‚Äôs only one resume slot available on Prentus, which makes that harder. So I‚Äôm doing my best to keep moving, but yeah ‚Äî I could really use some direction and there hasnt been a solid answer.   In short, yeah, career support has kinda felt like binge watching a YouTube playlist called ‚ÄúHow to Get a Job in Tech (but Without the Job Part).‚Äù   Thanks for hearing me out ‚Äî I appreciate the space to be honest about it.  Best, Jose
Thanks Jose. So you feel like the career services follow through and support was the part of the program that was most lacking?

Hi Justin,  Thank you so much for taking the time to reach out ‚Äî I really appreciate it.  To clarify, my intention wasn‚Äôt to single out one experience but rather to shine a light on a pattern I‚Äôve noticed across several individuals I‚Äôve connected with ‚Äî people who‚Äôve gone through similar programs and come out feeling somewhat adrift. I‚Äôm speaking both from my own experience and from the stories I‚Äôve heard from others along the way.  Personally, I‚Äôve had positive interactions with fellow alumni, and that peer network has been one of the strongest aspects of the journey. However, from the corporate side, I sometimes felt like just another number ‚Äî promised a transformative experience but left without the follow-through needed to succeed in today‚Äôs job market.  I understand that analytics and success metrics can be hard to measure precisely ‚Äî especially in something as human as career transitions ‚Äî but the often-quoted ‚Äú85% success rate‚Äù hasn‚Äôt matched what I‚Äôve seen or felt on the ground. Once the program ended, I expected there to be a stronger bridge into real job opportunities. Instead, I was handed a premium LinkedIn tool, which felt more like a placeholder than a solution ‚Äî especially in a job market that‚Äôs shifting daily due to tech layoffs, emerging trends like ‚Äúvibe hiring,‚Äù and the rise of non-traditional pathways.  When I brought this up to a job coach, their advice was to ‚Äústart a YouTube channel.‚Äù At that point, I couldn‚Äôt help but think: for the investment made, I could‚Äôve built one hell of a channel already.  I‚Äôm not trying to be cynical ‚Äî I‚Äôm reaching out because I care. I‚Äôm passionate about tech, about growth, and about finding meaningful work. I still believe in the mission. I just think there‚Äôs a gap between what‚Äôs promised and what‚Äôs actually delivered, and I‚Äôm hoping there‚Äôs room to bridge that ‚Äî together.  Thanks again for hearing me out.  Best, Jose

SUBJECT: Justin congrats
CONTENT: 1.Congrats on the announcement. Now shut that window and open the spreadsheets. Because these students don‚Äôt need another TED Talk about economic mobility. They need you to dissect every promise this company made, find the ones that were traps, and start cutting dead weight.  2. Stop listening to the applause. All those ‚ÄúCongrats Justin!‚Äù comments? They‚Äôre resume padding. If you want real credibility, go talk to the students still jobless after 9 months. You know‚Äîthe ones not posting, because they‚Äôre too burned out to play the algorithm game.  3. Make lies expensive. If Coding Temple is still using inflated placement stats, burying refund denials in fine print, or pushing students to become unpaid brand reps through ‚Äúbuilding in public,‚Äù shut it down. Publicly. Immediately. Because otherwise, you're just the fresh paint on a collapsing wall.  4. Don‚Äôt hide behind ‚Äúimpact.‚Äù You don‚Äôt need to "reimagine pathways to mobility"‚Äîyou need to give people what they paid for: jobs or their damn money back. Skip the vision boards. Start with:  Refund audits  Verified placement numbers  Stopping extensions from voiding guarantees  Actually helping, not spinning   5. Fire the funnel. If the only people getting hired are getting hired by Coding Temple, it‚Äôs not a career pipeline‚Äîit‚Äôs a human centipede of desperation. Stop turning students into staff just to pad outcomes. They‚Äôre not success stories. They‚Äôre survivors.  6. Own it or bounce. You‚Äôre not here to ‚Äúadvise‚Äù politely while sipping sparkling water. You‚Äôre here to blow the doors open, fix the broken trust, and stop the emotional debt people carry on top of their student loans. If you can‚Äôt do that with full power? Don‚Äôt let them use your name.  Beat regards,

SUBJECT: From one outdoor enthusiast to another - East Bay connection
CONTENT: Hi Thao,  I read about your journey at Clif Bar Foundation and am inspired by your personal journey and commitment to expanding outdoor access. I led Google's largest philanthropy team for the past decade and am always inspired seeing other corporate leaders find innovative ways to make impact.   My wife Sally and I founded Outdoorithm Collective last year here in Oakland, inspired by our own camping trips with our four girls, to help urban families discover the same joy we found in nature when we started backpacking together in 2005 (fueled by many, many Clif Bars!).  Your personal story of finding community in America deeply resonates. We're seeing similar transformative connections happen when diverse families camp together on public lands - people finding belonging, healing, and purpose.  We've hosted seven group trips so far, creating over 11,500 hours of outdoor experiences for urban families who might never have accessed these spaces otherwise. The transformation has been so meaningful - children climbing trees without fear, parents experiencing restorative sleep, families developing their own outdoor traditions that honor their cultural heritage.  Sally and I would love to grab coffee or jump on a call and share stories about our work creating inclusive outdoor spaces where environmental stewardship and community health naturally intersect.  No agenda beyond genuine connection between East Bay neighbors doing aligned work. Worth exploring?  All the best,  Justin

SUBJECT: Jackery Partnership Opportunity - Expanding Access to the Outdoors
CONTENT: Hi Ryan,  I noticed your leadership role at Jackery and wanted to connect. Given Jackery's impressive partnerships with WWF and the National Forest Foundation, I thought our missions might align. I recently left my role leading Google's Corporate Social Responsibility team to launch Outdoorithm Collective (www.outdoorithmcollective.org), an Oakland-based nonprofit getting families of color into camping through guided group trips. We're big Jackery fans - my family uses three of your batteries on every trip!  Would Jackery consider offering our nonprofit a group discount on 5-10 Jackery Explorer 600 Plus stations for our winter camping program? These would power fans for our propane heaters, making cold-weather camping accessible for first-time campers. We're scaling to serve tens of thousands of families of color in the coming years, and we'd love for these families to come to know and trust Jackery products as much as we do - advancing both our mission and Jackery's commitment to making green energy accessible to all.  Best regards,  Justin

All Best, JG  VISION ‚Äì A Category-Defining Opportunity  Just as Notion disrupted note-taking and Figma transformed design, VISION is poised to define the category of structured personal growth.  Founded by J.G. Boccella, a musician and artist losing his sight to retinitis pigmentosa, VISION is an AI-powered personal transformation platform that harnesses the power of creativity, structured goal-setting, and neuroscience-based habit formation to help people unlock their full potential.  By integrating behavioral psychology, mindfulness techniques, and the science of learning, VISION transforms goal-setting from a passive process into a dynamic, personalized, and visually engaging experience that fuels long-term growth.  The Opportunity  We are looking for a seasoned entrepreneur who has successfully scaled and exited a company, or someone who has been an early employee at a successful startup, to help take VISION to the next level.  This is a co-founder-level opportunity for a visionary builder who thrives on:  ‚Ä¢	Scaling an AI-powered product.  ‚Ä¢	Defining a high-growth strategy.  ‚Ä¢	Leading execution at the intersection of technology, personal development, creativity, and behavioral science.  ‚Ä¢	Harnessing the brain science of learning to drive habit formation, goal achievement, and long-term personal growth.

SUBJECT: New Futures for 450M Deaf across the globe
CONTENT: The Best Way to Predict the Future is to Create it (Peter Drucker), 2025 will be an evolutionary year for Bi/Dual ECE Language Acquisition and Visual Assistive Technology Communication for both Hearing & Deaf children...  We Thank You for your special efforts to help others to reach their full potential, and hope you will join Deaf-Tek Studio efforts to engage Hearing Societies to speak directly & communicate with Deaf Children & Adults... *If not a current focus area or interest to you, please accept our apology & respond to be removed from future updates.  If Communication problems are simply a lack of Hearing for 450M+ Deaf globally, how can we explain why global Societies have another 6/7+ Billion Hearing people are completely unable to communicate effectively with either Deaf Children or Adults to create a level of Inclusion that could provide Equitable Access to Education, Healthcare, Career Training & Inclusive Lifestyles for the overall benefit of both Hearing and Deaf populations‚Ä¶  Global Societies currently spend $890-B (US$) each year to engage & empower Deaf individuals to Learn and/or Communicate, but still manage to effectively accommodate only 30% of Deaf populations, primarily because they Fail to address the real Root Cause of ‚ÄòDelayed Learning‚Äô within the Deaf ECE Language Acquisition process‚Ä¶  *New ‚ÄòBest Practice‚Äô Research from NADC (Nat Assoc of Deaf Children), Gallaudet University & ZerotoThree.org has validated major Educational Childhood benefits of implementing Deaf Child Bi-Lingual Language Acquisition, synchronizing Spoken/Read/Write Languages with local Manual Sign Language as the new Best Practice Focus‚Ä¶   ‚ÄúThose crazy enough to think they can Change the World are those who will‚Äù‚Ä¶ ‚ÄúDeafness is a Lifetime Journey‚Äù and by adopting Bi-Lingual Language Acquisition for Preschool Deaf Child & Families we can significantly increase current ECE outcomes beyond WHO‚Äôs 30% levels with a unique Bi/Multi Visual Communication Protocol, capable of empowering Hearing populations to Communicate with Deaf persons in daily Society activities, while enhancing the lives of a myriad of other Disabled & Disenfranchised populations with similar Access & Inclusion issues‚Ä¶  Imagine Hearing individuals (Parent, Sibling, Healthcare Provider, Teacher, Employer) without any previous Sign Language experience‚Ä¶ being able to converse directly with Deaf Children & Adults, Healthcare Patients, Friends, Employees, & Customers & anytime, everywhere‚Ä¶ regardless of their Local Spoken or Sign Language!

SUBJECT: Request for Mentorship and Insights on Scaling Social Impact
CONTENT: Dear Justin Steele,  I hope this message finds you well. I am writing to express my deep respect for your exemplary work as a Social Impact Executive, Philanthropy Leader, and Fractional Chief Impact Officer, as well as your pioneering contributions to Public Interest Technology. Your unwavering commitment to driving meaningful change is both admirable and inspiring.    Allow me to introduce myself. My name is Mahmoud Jajah, and I have had the privilege of serving at the Ghana Embassy in Saudi Arabia, where I developed skills in diplomacy, international relations, and community outreach. Additionally, my tenure with the International Committee of the Red Cross provided me with a strong foundation in humanitarian aid, emergency response, and the integration of technology to address social challenges.    Currently, I am the founder of ZongoVation Hub, a social enterprise dedicated to empowering marginalized Zongo communities in Ghana through education, technology, and innovation. Through initiatives such as coding bootcamps, data science fellowships, and technology empowerment programs, we aim to create inclusive opportunities for underrepresented groups, with a strong emphasis on gender inclusivity in technology.    As I prepare to transition into working full-time with marginalized communities across Africa, I am seeking mentorship to deepen my impact and broaden the reach of my initiatives. Your extensive experience and strategic insights into scaling social impact initiatives, securing sustainable funding, and leveraging technology for transformative change would be invaluable.    I would be truly honored to have the opportunity to discuss these topics with you and learn from your expertise. Your guidance would greatly contribute to my efforts to foster sustainable development and social equity across Africa.    Thank you for considering my request. I look forward to the possibility of connecting with you and exploring how I can apply your insights to advance our shared vision for social good.    Warm regards,   Mahmoud Jajah   Founder & CEO, ZongoVation Hub   m.jajah@zongovationhub.org +233244980692

Hi Roxy! So good to hear from you. In response to your question, I think lived/work experience is probably the best path to learning how to lead others and influence culture. Organizational behavior and psychology can certainly inform this, but most people studying in those programs are headed towards academic/consulting careers, not people in practice. The Harvard Kennedy School has a mid-career program that does allow flexibility to take a number of elective courses around leadership and organizing that would be relevant, but it's a big cost (both in terms of tuition and opportunity cost). I've found that practice plus reflection (with an occasional high quality institutional training) can be a great way to grow and learn. Feel free to check out my book list on Good Reads if you want some book reading ideas :)

Hi Josie, good to be connected. To clarify, we had entire functions in the companies I worked in devoted to measuring brand and reputation lift. The Policy team rigorously tracked policymaker and other influencer engagement. The Comms team had dashboards measuring press hits and social media engagement. Our internal philanthropy team closely tracked senior exec engagement with our work. But there was very little infrastructure devoted to measuring social impact, and very few people up the chain asking for it.   Often there was a single FTE tracking outcomes reports from grantees, and typically their job was more to find good storytelling material than to ask hard questions about what social impact was being achieved. Ultimately, it rested upon us as individual grant makers to hold ourselves accountable for social impact and build measurement tracking into our grants. The business metrics were readily measured and easily available. The social impact metrics were hard to measure and not readily available. And if you can't manage what you don't measure, it made managing for social impact really tough, and mostly an exercise of self-discipline.  Hope that helps! I see you're involved in leading the Outdoor Diversity Alliance. My wife Sally and I co-founded both a social enterprise (Outdoorithm) and a nonprofit (Outdoorithm Collective) to support people who enjoy casual outdoor activities into becoming campers, particularly urban families of color in the case of our nonprofit work. Sally participated in the REI Embark program earlier this year. If you think there might be ways to advance some shared goals in the outdoor space together, we're up for a conversation!

I‚Äôm reaching out about the Aspen Institute‚Äôs Health Innovators Fellowship (HIF)‚Äîa truly unique program that inspires high-performing healthcare leaders across the U.S. to deepen their impact in solving our country‚Äôs most vexing social problems. Fellows are from sectors across the healthcare ecosystem and work in businesses, non-profits, government, and more. Each Fellow brings a different perspective but shares a commitment to improve U.S. health and health care. As a Fellow in the program, I can vouch that it‚Äôs been a transformative experience (or ‚Äúamong the most impactful experiences of my life‚Äù) that has challenged me to stretch myself to have more impact than I ever imagined. It has also provided me with both the tools and a community to support me and hold me accountable for my actions.   I share this program with you in the hopes that you and Google may be interested in learning about ways to get involved with the Fellowship. HIF is currently seeking new partnerships. Partners who provide financial support for the Fellowship have access to 100+ healthcare leaders in the industry as well as more than 3,000 entrepreneurial leaders from around the world who, like Health Fellows, are members of the Aspen Global Leadership Network. The Health Innovators Fellowship encourages its supporters to get to know and potentially collaborate with its Fellows on their work and the initiatives they undertake as part of the Fellowship.  If you are interested, I would like to set up a time to speak with you more about the program. I‚Äôd be happy to set up a brief introductory call for you to learn more. Attached to this note for your review is our HIF two-pager that provides more information on the Fellowship.     Thanks so much for your consideration; I look forward to hearing from you soon.   My very best wishes, Jay

SUBJECT: Considering a move from Google
CONTENT: Hi Christopher,  I hope you're doing well. It seems we have several points of overlap, from HBS and Google to our Washington State roots. I currently lead the Americas Team at Google.org, but with the significant reorganization happening at Google, I‚Äôm exploring new opportunities after a decade of leading social impact initiatives.  In my current role, I‚Äôve been leading one of Google‚Äôs major initiatives, the AI Opportunity Fund, across the U.S., Canada, and Latin America, where I focus on addressing the societal impacts of AI. In addition, I co-founded a social enterprise startup, Outdoorithm, where I‚Äôve been building our tech stack using AI, with the goal of helping urban families access and enjoy the outdoors through camping. I have an engineering degree, and I‚Äôve been applying that expertise extensively in our AI-driven solutions.  I‚Äôve had such positive experiences using Claude (AI still feels like magic!), both through the API and web UI, and I believe Anthropic offers one of the strongest genAI tools, particularly for general coding. Your commitment to social responsibility, as reflected in the company‚Äôs Public Benefit Corporation status and responsible development, is also something I admire.  While I understand Anthropic may not yet have a dedicated social impact team, I would love to explore whether my background might align with any social impact partnerships or advocacy work you‚Äôre considering in this space.  Would you be open to connecting me with someone at Anthropic who might explore these possibilities further?  Looking forward to hearing from you.  Best regards,  Justin

Hi Mo! Of course. Here's a slightly longer version with a couple of additional anecdotes. Feel free to edit.  I first met Mo when he launched my HBS Alumni Forum. I was so impressed by his impact on a new group and how quickly we made meaningful connections and began to help one another in meaningful ways. The structured process Mo implemented to bond a group of peers and help them identify ways they could support one another was so impactful that I still use many of the practices today in weekly team meetings and facilitated gatherings of community groups.  When I joined Google, I called upon Mo and Forum Resources Network to help us create a support community for our underrepresented employees. The impact was powerful and profoundly meaningful. We launched at the beginning of the pandemic and a time of uncertainty. With Mo‚Äôs help we launched 12 cohorts. Our team members met their cohorts virtually on Google Meet for two hours per month. These cohorts provided a rich environment for learning, growth, transformation and above all building meaningful relationships. Years later, I still run into participants who have stayed connected to these groups as a core part of their community of support.

Sandra Kojovic Project Delivery Associate at Arbolus Technologies sandra.kojovic@arbolus.com

I'd love to catch up in Sept and get your thoughts on some career stuff I'm thinking through too, especially around potentially making a career pivot into non profit leadership.¬†  Let me know!  -------- Shane, It was great speaking with you the other day.  As I mentioned, PeopleJoy partners with nonprofit institutions to create equity-based, student debt management and relief strategies that address the gender and racial wealth gaps, provide financial and mental wellness, and attract and retain talent.  I started the company after I graduated from Harvard Business School and my wife graduated from medical school with over $400,000 in student loans.  With the recently announced Limited PSLF Waiver Opportunity, which expires on October 31, 2022, more nonprofit employees than ever are now eligible for Public Service Loan Forgiveness. In the past 6 months alone, PeopleJoy has helped employees at these institutions receive over $2M in loan forgiveness.  We're getting some serious traction and are looking for advice on scaling within the nonprofit sector.   Given Google.org's expertise in the sector, I wanted to connect with Justin.  Thank you for offering to make an introduction!  Lastly, here is a link to a video testimonial from a CHOP attending we helped save $83,000 of student loan debt. https://share.vidyard.com/watch/fe4KyYVD1eu66BucRVU5vY?

CONTENT: Hi Justin,  Your profile jumped out at me, and I'd love to connect with you. I'm a recruiter with FuseCorps, a national non-profit focused on equitable recovery in local government.  We're looking for our next cohort of Executive Fellows, and your background is a strong fit for an opportunity we have in Oakland. Your experience with workforce development strategy would be a huge asset for the project we're working on.  I'd love to set up a call with you to share more about our organization and see if there's alignment or interest on your part. You can also learn more about us at: www.fusecorps.org  Or check out the fellowship opportunity here: https://jobs.crelate.com/portal/fusecorps/job/iwbewueobo7nbagnpkctfhh64r  Let me know if you'd like to set up an initial conversation.  All the best, Erin Carter  Manager of Fellow Recruiting Pronouns: she/her/hers FUSE Corps | www.fusecorps.org  ecarter@fusecorps.org (408) 684-8462  Erin Carter Recruiter & DEI Advocate (she/her)

Hi Justin  I hope all is well with you and that your family is safe/healthy during these interesting times.  I'm writing you to get some feedback and gauge an interest in participating in a program I'm helping ramp up.  Last year I launched a program for Softbank that aimed to train and deploy data scientist and AI engineers in Latin America.  We initially trained a cohort of 300 for the country of Colombia which led to a request from the country to train an additional 3000 this year.  This immediately got my gears turning around how we could do this in the US with an emphasis on the minority communities.  I'm currently finalizing cohorts in Detroit and Atlanta (i.e. my hometowns).  Given the current climate throughout the country I think it might be the right time to be more ambitious.    After a few conversations with my training partner and some leading tech and financial companies we've decided to launch Data Science for All - Empowerment.  The goal of this program is to train 10,000 people of color over the next 3 years in fields of Data Science, Machine Learning Coding, and AI engineering.  I'm attaching a detailed overview of the program.  Would love to get your feedback on the concept and any interest in participating.  Let me know if you have some time to chat this week or next week.  Thanks, TK _________________________________ Thomas K. Stewart +1.734.323.1267

Here‚Äôs an excerpt from a letter by LendingClub president Steve Alloca: ‚ÄúIn 2015, LendingClub embarked on a partnership with Opportunity Fund to expand access to capital to underserved small businesses. At first Opportunity Fund, the nonprofit CDFI, appeared outclassed by some of the Fortune 100 companies we also partnered with. But time and time again, Opportunity Fund has proven that they can out-execute and out-perform large public companies, while maintaining a mission-focus that reflects the best of what financial services can be. As a proud former Wells Fargo banker myself, I believe the bank will be similarly impressed with the impact and execution ability of Opportunity Fund. The LendingClub/Opportunity Fund partnership launched in 2016 as a first-of-its-kind, integrated fintech/CDFI online lending program. We began with a pilot focusing on the state of California and applicants through LendingClub who would otherwise be declined. It was such a success that we have expanded the program repeatedly, both in geographic and customer scope. To date, LendingClub‚Äôs partnership has helped Opportunity Fund originate more than 850 loans, totaling more than $28M, including 57% to entrepreneurs of color and 31% to women entrepreneurs. The program now operates in 45 states, serving a broader scope of credit profiles, thus also increasing the volume of small businesses served through Opportunity Fund. Small business owners who shop for a loan on LendingClub‚Äôs website are automatically run through Opportunity Fund‚Äôs credit box, using co-developed technology. Qualified applicants receive a seamless, automatic prequalified loan offer from Opportunity Fund. We believe this online loan offering is especially important as entrepreneurs of color are more likely to go online seeking loans than their white counterparts ‚Äì over half of the loans funded through the LC / Opportunity Fund partnership have gone to entrepreneurs of color. Our partnership thus far has proven successful by combining LendingClub‚Äôs technology expertise with Opportunity Fund‚Äôs track record of community impact. This groundbreaking partnership will continue leveraging the strengths of each organization to drive scale at a whole new level through Opportunity Fund‚Äôs new strategic plan. We believe this partnership is a breakthrough program for building and sustaining the economic empowerment of diverse communities, and the success of small businesses everywhere. That‚Äôs one reason LendingClub is eager and enthusiastic to support Opportunity Fund‚Äôs Strategic Plan (2109-2023), and the Inclusive Lending Platform roadmap for national scale and long-term impact.‚Äù

Essentially borrowers who come to lending club for a small business loan are seamlessly offered a loan from Opportunity Fund (if they fit the criteria of our partnership parameters). The small business lending they were doing before this most recent announcement is now either referred to us or to Funding Circle (per a predefined model)

Sure - referral is just part of the partnership. This press release has a lot of great info about our relationship: https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/lendingclub-partners-with-opportunity-fund-and-funding-circle-increasing-financial-inclusion-and-small-businesses-access-to-credit-300835943.html

We are thrilled to invite you to accept this award and to join us on Thursday, May 10th in San Francisco to receive your recognition while spending a fun evening with Playworks! In addition to the ritual of cocktails, dinner and awards, the guests at Get in the Game play foursquare and shoot hoops, among other games.  Get in the Game Thursday, May 10, 2018 Regency Ballroom in San Francisco. 5:30 VIP Reception 7:30 Dinner program As part of your Most Inspiring Leader recognition, we will coordinate a time to produce a brief video of you at your office. The video, part of the evening‚Äôs program, will serve as an introduction to you and your work. We also invite you to speak for 3-4 minutes upon accepting your award. We'll work closely with you or with your staff to coordinate all logistics, including car service to and from the event and seating for you and your guests. We're happy to discuss pre-event media but welcome any thoughts or suggestions from your office. We hope that you will  Finally, if your schedule allows, we would appreciate the chance to sit down with you briefly sometime before the event so that we may get better acquainted. If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact Deb Parsons,

SUBJECT: Re: Message replied: Re: I am not stalking you...
CONTENT: Hi Patricia, thanks for the note.¬† I appreciate hearing your reflections.¬†  I agree that nonprofits can add a lot of value to companies through their  engagement of employees (though I sometimes wish the value flowed more in  the other direction during those engagements), but as you said, there are a  lot of nonprofit who compete for that role, so again, back to the "buyers  market" dynamic.¬† In the end, the personal humility of the corporate leader  ends up mattering a lot to keep the balance of power in the right place.  No worries on confusing the Justins!¬† Best of luck with the application.  Justin

SUBJECT: Re: I am not stalking you...
CONTENT: Hi Justin,    I've thought about your response below from time to time, and I reluctantly agree about the power asymmetry. I would like to think that humans (and even corporations composed of humans) are more altruistic, but... I tend to be a bit idealistic. That being said, we have a couple of (amazing) corporate partners at Playworks, who are consistently reaching out to us desiring the types of engagement events that we can provide for their employees, giving project teams a bonding experience with their peers, along with the gratifying feeling of giving back. That was my original thought, but when I reflected a bit, I realized that although we offer an optimal experience, there are many other nonprofits which could fit the bill as well and ... would love to. Thus, the power disparity. Sigh...    I'm actually writing to you today, because our COO submitted a proposal in consideration for the Google Impact Challenge Grant, and within the grant, she erroneously stated that Playworks has a relationship with you (Justin Steele). She meant to state that we have a relationship with Justin Philips, who works in finance in Sunnyvale. He is a Silicon Valley Board member. She sent me a note, somewhat devastated about her error, and I advised her that I would reach out to you (and our Board member, Justin) and explain the mistake.  Our apologies.     Wishing you a wonderful weekend!    Patricia

SUBJECT: Re: I am not stalking you...
CONTENT: Hi Patricia, yes, my colleague Chelsea Seabron is on the Oakland/East Bay  board, and I believe I've met their Executive Director.¬† Thanks for the  note.¬† Would love to hear your thoughts sometime on the interdependency  between companies and nonprofits.¬† It's hard to overcome the "buyers  market" dynamic; there are a finite amount of money chasing a lot of worthy  causes, and just like in the marketplace, that creates a power asymmetry.¬†  It doesn't mean that nonprofits don't have a lot of value to add to  companies, but it does mean that companies will tend to be in the drivers  seat as the ones holding the "buying power."  Justin

SUBJECT: I am not stalking you...

I think you've met some of my colleagues at Playworks. I so wanted to comment on the 'power differential' conundrum you referred to (corps and non profits). I think we're more interdependent than we think!  Anyway, thank you for adding such a multi-dimensional perspective to the conversation at lunch!  I hope our paths cross again.    Patricia

Hi Justin,    It is great to be connected. We at Root & Rebound (rootandrebound.org) would love to connect with you about our work, as I have seen over the years Google.org's passion for and commitment to criminal justice reform.   Root & Rebound is a reentry legal resource center transforming lives across California by empowering individuals in reentry to thrive and succeed. We are lawyers and advocates, helping people navigate the challenges of collateral consequences and legal barriers post-involvement in the justice system through a model of public education, advocacy, and policy reform.   Root & Rebound has reached over 40,000 people to date through our programs and services because of our commitment to partnerships and cross-sector collaborations. Partners include government agencies, parole and probation officers, employers, directly impacted and currently incarcerated individuals, social workers, educators, and workforce development professionals, among others. As a result, our work intentionally convenes unlikely partners, creating cooperation between traditionally hostile communities to foster community cohesion, increase access to equal opportunity for people and communities impacted by incarceration.  I would  greatly appreciate the opportunity to tell you more. We are headquartered in Oakland, launching sites in LA and Fresno this year, and its an exciting time for us to connect!  All best, Katherine

SUBJECT: RE: Racial Justice Grants and Impact Investing
CONTENT: Thanks Justin, impressive and makes sense given your magnitude (focusing on systemic work as well as direct service). I appreciate you responding and look forward to continuing to stay up-to-date on Google.org's work, us smaller foundations have a lot to learn from you!

SUBJECT: RE: Racial Justice Grants and Impact Investing
CONTENT: Hi Janice, thanks for reaching out. While we have invested in organizations like Kiva in the past, we don't currently engage in Impact Investing. Our racial justice work is also more focused on challenging systemic racial bias in dominate systems than providing services to excluded people (though we do engage in work with a more targeted impact on these communities through our other portfolios).

SUBJECT: Racial Justice Grants and Impact Investing
CONTENT: Hello Justin: I run a $50 million private foundation in Denver. I just read that Google.org increased its investment in racial justice programming. To the extent that Google is exploring impact investment, I would love to talk with you further about ways to partner. We are passionate about giving minorities opportunities to be successful entrepreneurs, through capital lending, entrepreneurship training and access to mentorship. We believe we have the opportunity to invest in small business, beyond grantmaking, and through loan and equity investment, bringing new jobs to those most at-risk.   Kind regards, Janice Fritsch 720-260-0146

That's have been most excellent!  Mostly still building the buy-in from tribal leaders across the state, but am building up nice momentum with that group and expect to have a solid core of tribes trying to get into charter authorization.  Have to pull a few stakeholders together and invent some stuff - mostly policy and legal frameworks we can hand to tribes as in many respects we're kind of inventing the wheel here mixing the arcane world of charter law with the potentially fraught world of tribal politics and Indian law.  And that's the easy part!  Have three fellows from the NACA Inspired School Network starting work on schools in three towns in Oklahoma next month, so I'll be supporting them on community and grass-roots building, and then we'll start the formal training and consulting with tribes sometime early Fall, looking to have them authorizing schools within a year so that we might open doors the '18-'19 school year on the first wave of schools. CONTENT: Hi Justin,  My name is Sonia Gonzales. I'm sorry I was unable to connect following yesterday's NCG workshop on race and philanthropy. I am moved by the increasing commitment by philanthropy to issues of racial justice and equity.   Your story about bringing Google to invest on issues of racial justice resonated with me. I am the Executive Director of the California Bar Foundation. Recently, I've moved my board to refine our mission strategy wherein our investments now are focused exclusively on increasing, diversity, equity and inclusion in the California justice system, as a matter of access to justice for all Californians. In effect, we are changing the narrative in the community around the lack of diversity to one which directly acknowledges the racial inequities in representation in the legal profession and in the justice system as matters of social justice. As with your experience, it has not been easy to move this organization to this place. The 35 statewide high level partners, general counsel and judges on the board are all at very different places in terms of their own racial consciousness in this area in a profession that is the least diverse in the country.  All of that is to say I appreciate that you pushed Google to invest in racial justice work. We've all got to use our positions in whichever industry, at whatever level of impact to advance the conversation. Like you, I am relatively new to philanthropy and am always looking to connect with like minded leaders of color. Our offices are based in San Francisco. Please let me know if you have the time to connect for coffee sometime.  Looking forward to it!  Sonia Gonzales sgonzales@calbarfoundation.org

SUBJECT: RE: Request for Info on Google.org Partners
CONTENT: Hi Roy, I'm happy to explore whether connecting makes sense.  To respect both of our time, can you give me a high-level sense for how you might envision us partnering? My work currently covers investments in the Bay Area community (generally where Googlers live and work) as well as racial justice work in the U.S. to eliminate racial bias within the criminal justice and educational systems. My investments are generally $500K-$1M grants to support projects that are transformational for the organization and the community it serves.  I've included some questions below that I generally ask myself as I consider partnerships. If you can articulate a compelling partnership opportunity, I'm happy to talk it through with you. I'm also fine with generally staying in touch if you don't see a current opportunity to partner but want to keep the door open for something that may develop down the road.  Looking forward to hearing your thoughts.  Justin   Questions to ask yourself (in order of importance):  - Does your approach disrupt the equilibrium of an unsustainable and unjust system that leads to social and economic exclusion?  If you were to ramp down, would the change remain or disappear? - Is the project rooted in "first principles," breaking from established wisdom, boiling down to fundamental truths, and rooted in invention and discovery? - Are you taking direct action by creating a new product or service that directly improves the lives of the socially and economically excluded? - Will key opinion formers and policymakers be more likely to view Google favorably as a result of a partnership? - Will the general public be more likely to believe that Google gives back to the community as a result of a partnership? - Will the organization be able to leverage Google in unique ways by collaborating with our teams and finding new ways to utilize our products/services?

SUBJECT: Request for Info on Google.org Partners
CONTENT: Hi Justin,  I'm reaching out on behalf of YESS Foundation a 501c3, formed in 1989 by then San Francisco Giants Pitcher Mike LaCoss. To date, he has raised $500,000 with nearly 100 individual and organization recipients, both here in Tulare County and abroad to Dominican Republic & Uganda.   For over 3 years, I have worked as Mike‚Äôs Director of Production at iBaseballChannel.com, untold baseball stories directly from the pros. Along the way we created a Narrative, which then produced a Purpose, and now has put us on a Mission.  This mission combines our production skill with a character-building curriculum and hands-on outreach, creating positive influence for students via Major Leaguers. The content captured by us via each community visit would include a Road Show of the crew, stories from the Player-to-Player interaction and a motivating Player-to-Youth forum with a different professional guest and youth group each trip. Our focus is California due to its width of diversity and many kids without proper resources.   We currently have and receive by the day Letters of Support for this from former Major Leaguers, Educators/Supervisors, and representatives of Youth Baseball Organizations. The YESS Foundation itself has registered for Google for Nonprofits and we are interested to know the potential of partnering with Google.org to help empower our mission. Beginning with an impactful first-year production window, we feel there's true potential to create a positive, repeatable formula for character-building through the game and its personalities.   Thank you for your time, and we'd welcome any suggestions as to how we can further connect with Google.org. We recognize any partnership involves a process and simply put, we‚Äôd like the opportunity to be considered as a viable outlet for character building for students, powered by Google‚Äôs tools of connectivity, successful because of the wealth of Major League resources ready, willing and able to help.  Best wishes, thanks!

SUBJECT: requesting a meeting
CONTENT: Hello Justin -       I run the nonprofit Our City Forest which for 20 years has been greening these communities... providing/planting 65,000+ large shade trees and free arborist services for literally thousands of parks, schools and streets.      We are now developing a large-scale neighborhood lawn conversion and water conservation program, named Lawnbusters, for launching next fall.    We have an opportunity for a sizable state grant this fall but must come up with significant local matching funding first.      I am reaching out to build a circle of local support - bringing together foundations and corporations wanting to participate in this important transformation for the South Bay.  The myriad human health benefits of our efforts as well as the environmental, aesthetic and community development benefits should certainly be regarded by local interests, yet local financial support from our beloved local corporations, is nearly nonexistent.      How might we best show Google that investing in our mission supports the company directly by making this community a desirable place to live for its employees -- plus, it is improving the quality of life for those living in low-income neighborhoods as well.    If you'd like a to take a peek at our website - ourcityforest.org - you will be able to see our extensive array of programs and services.      We would very much appreciate hearing your ideas for strategies and potential partnerships for the important work that we do. Please email or call at your convenience.    Thank you so much!    Rhonda Berry  408-799-9502

SUBJECT: StreetIssue.org
CONTENT: Hi Justin,  I'm a co-founder of StreetIssue.org, and I'm not going to lie, I saw you donated to HandUp, and thought you might like to help us too.  StreetIssue.org is radically different from many other homeless programmes in that it targets chronic homelessness (not just one offs) and is self sustainable.   Founded by a small team in San Francisco, StreetIssue is very loosely based on the subscription model of WorldVision, where individuals and family have the option to connect with the person they sponsor. StreetIssue is providing a number of products and services that the homeless themselves, or volunteers (for those unable) can sell on a subscription basis that provide substantial value to the sponsor/consumer. From that, the homeless earn their own right, be empowered, and self determined to make a regular income. We believe that by selling a $7 service product like a discount card, curated content (maybe their life story with updates), or other products will be attractive to most people. If a homeless person receives 300 sponsors, that will be enough for rent, food, and most basic needs.   We intend to work with existing service providers in the area to provide options when the homeless collect payment. We want to give them every opportunity to become better, more stable and healthy. We believe in intrinsic motivation over extrinsic motivation, so have no intention of forcing the homeless into services, but may only offer the service initially to those who are serious about change and are immediately capable. These first people in the programme can then become leaders and mentors for the next wave of people.  We believe this model is scalable globally, and intrinsically different from other solutions - as at its here for the long term.  If you choose not to help personally, please share this with others that may be interested, or our meetup!  http://www.meetup.com/StreetIssue-Long-term-incomes-for-the-homeless-SF/  Thanks so much Andy
