SUBJECT: Re: Message replied: RE: Re: Time to Talk
CONTENT: Hi Udi, given the small size of our team and time constraints (as you can  imagine), we don't have the capacity to meet with folks interested in  learning more about Google.org outside of windows when we're hiring.¬†  In terms of answers to your questions:      * Google.org invests in projects that are having social impact (broadly       defined - within the Bay Area, it's focused on jobs, housing, poverty       alleviation in low-income and underserved communities), inspire our       Googlers, and reflect positively on the company in the community.¬† We       don't run any of our own initiatives but rather invest in the       capacity of nonprofit organizations doing work in the gaps where       Google Inc. does not operate.     * I suppose the team size reflects the organization's willingness to       invest in these kinds of initiatives.¬† We are very generous with our       financial and product resources, but we have limited headcount.¬† I       don't foresee any significant expansion, but Google moves fast and       anything could happen.     * Google.org works closely with most internal groups working towards       social impact, though we don't interface too deeply with the       sustainability folks.     * My degrees have influenced a significant part of my approach to the       work.¬† I focused on nonprofit management in business school and feel       very comfortable with strategy, finance, marketing, etc.¬† I focused       on urban social policy for my MPA and feel like I know just enough to       be dangerous when it comes to policy and programs around urban       inequality.¬† I would say the MPA was more of a "nice to have", but I       am able to stretch myself a lot further because I have it. I hope that helps.¬† Let me know if you have any follow up questions.  Justin

I wanted to let you know that ProInspire is now recruiting for the 2015 ProInspire Fellowship.  We are looking for top professionals with 2-5 years of business experience who want to work for a leading social sector organization in DC or SF. I would appreciate if you can share the posting below with your networks, or update your status to say:   ProInspire is now accepting applications from outstanding young business professionals who want to change the world. Round 1 applications due Jan. 26 and Round 2 due Feb. 23! http://www.proinspire.org/fellows/     Thanks,  Monisha    What would you do if you could change the world?  At ProInspire, we develop leaders at all levels for organizations addressing the world‚Äôs greatest challenges. We were named by the Chronicle of Philanthropy as one of 7 Nonprofits to Watch in 2015. We are currently recruiting top professionals with 2-5 years of business experience to be a part of our flagship program, the ProInspire Fellowship: http://www.proinspire.org/fellows/. This highly competitive program offers targeted positions with leading social sector organizations, monthly trainings with a cohort of peers, a coach, and a network to support career growth. Fellows spend one year working in a role focused on analysis, finance, fundraising, marketing, operations, or strategy.     Program Overview  ProInspire Fellows bring strong skills and experience to their hiring organization, and a desire to learn through on-the-job experience and professional development. The Fellowship program runs for 12 months, with the training program starting in August 2015. Fellows work full-time for a ProInspire partner, and participate in our industry leading professional development program. ProInspire‚Äôs professional development includes orientation, Fellows retreat, monthly workshops, coaching, and leadership development projects. Fellows also receive career/graduate school support.     Annual compensation and health benefits are provided by the hiring organization. Compensation is $45,000 in Washington, DC and $47,500 in San Francisco Bay Area.     Roles for past ProInspire Fellows include:   ‚Ä¢	ACCION International: Impact Investing Fellow  ‚Ä¢	FHI 360: Strategy Fellow  ‚Ä¢	Global Giving: Operations Fellow  ‚Ä¢	Cesar Chavez Public Charter Schools for Public Policy: Marketing Fellow  ‚Ä¢	Meals on Wheels: Finance Fellow  ‚Ä¢	Share Our Strength: HR Fellow  ‚Ä¢	San Francisco Child Abuse Prevention Center: Data Fellow  ‚Ä¢	Year Up Bay Area: Communications Fellow    Selection Criteria  Successful candidates will have:  ‚Ä¢	A minimum of two years of business or fundraising experience by August 2015  ‚Ä¢	Passion for using their business skills to have a positive impact on society  ‚Ä¢	Humility and eagerness to learn   ‚Ä¢	Demonstrated initiative, self-direction and a ‚Äúcan-do‚Äù attitude  ‚Ä¢	Adaptability in ambiguous situations and demonstrated ability to learn quickly  ‚Ä¢	Strong analytical, problem solving, and project management skills  ‚Ä¢	Willingness to live in the SF Bay Area or Washington D.C. for the program    To Apply  Apply online at http://www.proinspire.org/fellows/apply/. Round 1 applications are due Jan. 26th and Round 2 applications are due Feb. 23rd. Candidates will be considered for placement dates and locations based on their application preferences. Details and further information regarding the application and selection process can be found at http://www.proinspire.org/fellows/selection/.

Please share this with your network!    ProInspire is accepting applications from business professionals who want to change the world. ProInspire focuses on expanding the social sector's talent pipeline, developing professionals, and increasing diversity in the sector. We are passionate about accelerating social impact and being catalysts of outstanding performance. We have been operating in the Washington DC region since 2009 and in the San Francisco Bay Area since 2012. Previous ProInspire Fellows come from across the U.S. with experience at Accenture, Bain, BCG, Deloitte, General Mills, Goldman Sachs, Google, JP Morgan, and other leading companies.    Program Overview  The Fellowship program runs for 12 months, with start dates in April 2013 and August 2013. Hiring partners include organizations focused on community development, education, health, human rights, international development, microfinance, impact investing, and youth development. Roles for past ProInspire Fellows include:  ‚Ä¢         ACCION International: Impact Investing Fellow  ‚Ä¢         FHI 360: Strategy Fellow  ‚Ä¢         Global Giving: Operations Fellow  ‚Ä¢         Cesar Chavez Public Charter Schools: Marketing Fellow  ‚Ä¢         Share Our Strength: HR Fellow  ‚Ä¢         SingleStop USA: Special Projects Fellow  ‚Ä¢         Year Up Bay Area: Communications Fellow    Fellows participate in orientation, a mandatory Fellows retreat, monthly workshops, coaching, and leadership development projects. Fellows also receive career/graduate school support. After the program, Fellows stay in the social sector, find other career opportunities, or attend graduate school. Annual compensation of $45,000 and health benefits are provided by the hiring organization.    Successful candidates will have:  ‚Ä¢         A minimum of two years of business experience by August 2013  ‚Ä¢         Passion for using their business skills to have a positive impact on society  ‚Ä¢         Humility and eagerness to learn  ‚Ä¢         Demonstrated initiative, self-direction and a "can-do" attitude  ‚Ä¢         Adaptability in ambiguous situations and demonstrated ability to learn quickly  ‚Ä¢         Strong analytical, problem solving, and project management skills  ‚Ä¢         Willingness to live in the Bay Area or Washington D.C. for the program    To Apply:  Candidates applying for April start dates should submit their application through our website by Friday, February 1st, 2013. Candidates applying for August start dates should submit their application by Friday, March 1st, 2013 for priority consideration. Apply online at http://www.proinspire.org/fellows/apply/.

Many thanks, all best, Daniel   daniel@mouse.org  MOUSE Business Development Manager   About MOUSE:  MOUSE is a NYC-based  innovative youth development organization that empowers underserved youth to learn, lead and create with technology, preparing them with skills essential for their academic and career success. The MOUSE Squad program trains students to become digital media and technology experts in their schools, improving the use of technology to enhance learning, while also building confidence and developing skills for 21st century innovation. MOUSE operates in more than 230 schools across the country, serving over 170,000 students each year. MOUSE currently employs ten full-time staff, one part-time staff member, and an array of consultants and contractors.   Position Overview:  MOUSE is seeking a dynamic, self-motivated Business Development Manager who will drive the continued expansion of MOUSE programs across the country, (currently in 14 states), with a particular focus on school districts and the charter schools community, as well as in other learning spaces used by young learners.  The Business Development Manager will also help identify, cultivate and close grant opportunities with corporations and foundations, and revenue-generating partnerships with corporations and large non-profit organizations, including licensing of selected MOUSE intellectual property.   This position provides an exciting opportunity for someone who thrives in an entrepreneurial  and mission-driven organization and welcomes the challenge of a fast-paced environment.   The Business Development Manager will report directly to the Director of Development .  The position is based in MOUSE‚Äôs office in Manhattan/NYC; some travel is required.    Responsibilities Include:   The Business Development Manager will:   Identify, cultivate and close on a specific number of new revenue-generating relationships each year, and achieve or exceed specific overall revenue goals.. Work closely with the Director of Development and the Executive Director to leverage MOUSE‚Äôs existing networks for qualified prospects and leads. Work closely with MOUSE‚Äôs program team in onboarding of new MOUSE clients, to ensure client satisfaction with program implementation, after-sales service and ongoing MOUSE relationship. Give MOUSE‚Äôs learning design team feedback from prospects and clients so that MOUSE can modify current offerings to meet learner needs and create offerings that meet as-yet unmet learner demand. Create viable sales strategies for new MOUSE products and services, including licensing of intellectual property outside of existing MOUSE membership channels. Participate in budgeting & planning process including forecasting & monthly reporting review. Manage sales/prospects database in Salesforce and provide reports as needed. Assist in planning fundraising events. Represent MOUSE externally at conferences, workshops and special events. Other projects as they arise and time allows.  Required Skills, Experience and Abilities: Bachelor degree and 4-6 years of relevant professional experience required, an MBA will be a plus.  Passion for MOUSE‚Äôs mission and/or nonprofit experience is required. Demonstrated success in sales and business development; preferably in education or a social enterprise environment Comfortable attaining or exceeding clearly specified goals. Experience working with individuals of diverse backgrounds (students, teachers, administrators, corporate partners, etc.). Self-starter, highly flexible, results-driven, a fast learner able to juggle multiple priorities. Superb written and verbal communication skills, familiarity with contracts a strong plus.. Technology skills are highly desirable including ease with Excel, Google Apps, Salesforce. Desire to learn and grow in the role and with the organization.  Some national travel will be required.   Salary: In order to attract and retain highly qualified candidates, MOUSE offers a competitive salary with a generous benefits package including health/vision/dental/LTD/Life, 403b/matching, Flex Spending, summer flex hours, professional development opportunities.   To Apply:  Please e-mail your cover letter (that clearly explains why the Business Development Manager position at MOUSE is uniquely suited to your talents) and resume to Attn: Business Development Manager Search at info@mouse.org.  No calls please.  You will only be contacted if we are interested in pursuing your candidacy.   Initial closing date for applications: Fri, Sept. 19, 2014.     Additional information about MOUSE can be found at www.mouse.org.  EEO

SUBJECT: Exciting Opportunity at Google!
CONTENT: Hi Justin,    I am Michelle and part of Google‚Äôs recruiting team. I have an exciting opportunity that I would love to discuss with you. SUBJECT: Commit!, Director of Early Childhood
CONTENT: Dear Justin,    Commit! is a partnership of Dallas area organizations who are (i) committed to the transformative power of education and (ii) are willing to work together to ensure that all students in Dallas County graduate and succeed in college, career, and life. The guiding principles of Commit! include a strong focus on data driven decision-making, supported by facilitating collaborative action while advocating for and aligning funding around proven strategies.   Commit! is seeking a Director of Early Childhood, who will serve as senior strategist and project manager for initiatives that enhance children‚Äôs educational progress from birth through 3rd grade. SUBJECT: RE: What Can I Contribute to Year Up?
CONTENT: Justin,    I am currently living in Charlotte, NC and I realize that unfortunately, there is not a Year Up site local to Charlotte.  When I first started thinking about Year Up, I was interested in volunteering, and the more I think about it, I would really like to explore the possibility of a career.  From looking over the Volunteer and Careers pages on Year Up's website, I see a couple places where I could add value but I guess I'd like to get a broader understanding of the different departments, how each branch/department operates, and just get your input and advice as someone who works inside the company.  I may end up learning more and see that I'd be better suited for Volunteer opportunities and that a full time job may not be the best fit for Year Up or myself.  But the opportunity to help others and be part of such an amazing organization is something I cannot pass up with out at least exploring the possible options.    Is there any chance you could be available for a few minutes to have a brief phone conversation and answer a few questions for me?  I can make myself available any time day or night at your convenience and would be happy to make a donation to Year Up in your name to thank you for your time.  If that is not a possibility, I'd greatly appreciate it if you could point me in the right direction of anyone else you'd recommend.    Thanks again for your time and consideration.    Best,    Jeremy

SUBJECT: What Can I Contribute to Year Up?
CONTENT: Mr. Steele,     Since graduating from college, I've spent 3 years working in recruiting in Charlotte & Atlanta. I spend half my day networking, discussing hiring needs & company expectations with managers from companies across the Carolinas. The other half of my day, I review resumes, talk to candidates, prep them for interviews, & manage a team of recruiters who spend 100% of their days doing the same. As you can imagine, I understand the need and the difficulty that companies have finding dedicated, qualified candidates to fill increasingly demanding and technology-driven jobs.     As a professional in recruiting, I see how much value Year Up can add. That said, your business model was not what drew me to Year Up- I have been a mentor with Big Brothers Big Sisters for 2 years. When I saw the Year Up alumni on 60 Minutes talking about how the program changed their lives, I saw my little brother, Obi. When I started spending time with him, he was a shy 11 yr old who struggled with school and didn't like speaking up to give his order to a waitress. Behind an introverted 11 yr old was the confident, energetic 13 yr old I see today. He smiles, cracks jokes, and orders extra honey mustard with literally every meal. The difference that can be made in someone‚Äôs life by giving a chance/investing time is absolutely unfathomable.The contributions on a micro level that can be made by becoming a Big Brother are unbelievable. I believe the work you do at Year Up is an incredible example of what can be done on a macro level.     I send this message because I want to know how I can get involved. I understand that you are probably a very busy person but I wanted to see if I could have a few minutes of your time to speak. Given my knowledge of recruiting, hiring, & networking + my personal connection to the mission of Year UP, I feel that I would be an asset to your organization and would greatly appreciate the opportunity to tell you why.     Thanks in advance,   Jeremy Morris

SUBJECT: Retained executive search firm seeking referral: Strategy Consultant
CONTENT: Hi Justin,     I am a consultant with Lone Aspen LLC, a retained executive search firm. I wanted to introduce myself and an opportunity with one of my clients, in case you might know someone interested in the role. I hope you don't mind the direct contact, as I am not seeking to link directly with your network. Your background caught my attention because of your prior consulting roles and engineering experience.    We have been retained by a boutique consulting firm with a strong 20-year track record, to find an engagement director for their expanding strategy consulting practice. The company is best known for their thought leadership in Lean Six Sigma methodologies, has both commercial and government clients, and has many consultants with engineering backgrounds. The ideal candidate will have an MBA with 1-5 years of consulting experience and 5-10 years total professional experience, both in operating roles and leading consulting engagements.     Our client's firm is entrepreneurial and collegial, less bureaucratic and rigid than many larger firms; their consultants truly enjoy the craft of problem-solving, and they are rewarded for individual performance. The virtual structure allows consultants to live where they choose, and travel to the client as needed. Naturally, the firm has attracted many alumni from top strategy firms and presents an outstanding long-term opportunity.     Perhaps you know someone - a former colleague or acquaintance - who might be interested in such an opportunity? If so, I'd appreciate the opportunity to speak with you further.     Thank You and Best Regards,     Chris

Told in large part by Year Up students and graduates in their own words, this book shares the challenges of chasing the American dream when you‚Äôre stuck on the wrong side of the Opportunity Divide. I would greatly appreciate your support in making it a success. You can help most by purchasing a copy of the book, sharing a review on Amazon.com, and recommending the book on LinkedIn, Facebook, and Twitter. All of our proceeds will be donated to the Year Up program.    To learn more about the book and to purchase a copy, please visit http://www.yearupbook.com.

Hey Justin,    HBS is great. The 1st semester was a bit intense but I remembered the Comm-School being a pretty similar 2 year structure with the 1st semester being the worst so that certainly helped manage my expectations. As for socially, I got a bit of a pass from feeling that FOMO syndrome on all the social stuff going on since my husband and I were expecting our son right after 1st semester ended (we ended 12/16 and he was born 12/21 so perfect timing..lol), which I think helped take off a lot of the pressure to try to be at everything but my sectionmates often remind me that I won't get off that easy in the spring :-) All in all, it's been everything I had hoped for. Academics are obviously a huge piece of it but so was getting a bit of time off from work to spend a bit more time with family and welcome our newest addition so this way he'll be about a 1 1/2 before I have to go back to work full time. I'm recruiting for consulting -- mainly McKinsey & Bain. Coming from PwC and working in professional services, I just felt like there was still so much more to see there before narrowing down to a particular fuction / industry / company and I feel like consulting will give me the best opportunity to explore that. We're looking at Atlanta (probably our top choice), Boston, DC or other Southern offices for full-time. I know you did Bain / Atlanta so any insight you can provide there would be great. I've talked with several folks down there and a few wahoos but another perspective never hurts.    Also, I'd been meaning to reach out for awhile since an email that you sent to AASU re: a position at your company came across my inbox. I sent it along to a few sectionmates that I knew were looking for positions in that space so hopefully you heard back from a few people.    Send the family my best!    Emily

Hi Emily, great to hear from you.  Congrats on HBS!  I didn't realize that you were there.  How has it been so far?  I remember 1st semester RC year being pretty overwhelming (more socially than academically).  What are you looking to do post-HBS?

Hi Tolu, my apologies for letting your note slip through the cracks!  Between you writing and me responding, my wife and I have had another baby, I've torn my achilles playing basketball and had surgery, and we graduated another class of students.  It's been a busy season of life!    I appreciate you offering to call Brandy.  We worked out a solution for the SAIC interns eventually (at least for one of them).    Your new project sounds great!  If at some point you are interested in bringing on some of our alums, let me know.  They come out with really strong technical skills, and although they wouldn't have a college degree, they would have some college credit through our program.    Take care Tolu.    Best,    Justin

Justin,    Good to hear from you, hope all is good with you and your fam. I'm actually a contractor at SAIC, not an full time employee so my ability to leverage SAIC resources is pretty limited. I'm in the Health Sciences Business unit working on a specific DoD contract which is pretty limited in scope (only 4 people work on it.) I'm also not sure how much longer i'll be here since my contract is on a contingent basis, basically I'm not sure how much i could actually offer these interns in the way of mentoring, (at least in an official SAIC capacity.) I have very few contacts here and I've found that people (at least in my dept.) are not very receptive to being approached.    The bulk of my current time is spent building my current project. I plan to use the company to train college graduates in Oracle technology with the goal of eventually staffing them to projects. It's still very much in a preliminary stage but i envision being able to build a team of trained, clearable people that have the skills that government IT contracts require.Could this be something that would potentially be useful to your non profit (if not now maybe in the future?)     In any case i wish i could give you a more helpful answer. There is a guy i work with Brandy Dawkins, he's a senior technical guy on another project, he might be someone you could talk to that might be able to help guide you further. He's been here for about 7yrs and he knows a lot of people in SAIC. If you want i can have him call you.

Hi Tolu, I hope you're well.  It's been a while!  I finished up my MBA last May, and I've been working in D.C. for a nonprofit called Year Up.  We train urban young adults for IT internships, and we have several interns at SAIC in the ISBU Mission Partner Solutions Operations area.  They seem to be struggling to get substantive work, and I thought I would reach out to you to see if you would be open to mentoring them a bit.  If this is something that would be of interest, I'm happy to chat with you more about the program.  If not, no worries at all, I know you must be a busy man!    Best,    Justin

Teach For America is looking for a results oriented team manager with strong writing ability and project management skills for the Senior Managing Director of Shared Support & Communications position.      If you know great people with 7 or more years of work experience (this position could become Vice President level), please let me know. Please feel free to share this widely.     Happy new year!   --------------------------------------------------------------------------------  Senior Managing Director, Shared Support & Communications, Growth, Strategy & Development team    Teach For America is seeking a Senior Managing Director of Shared Support & Communications to play a critical leadership role in managing the vision and execution of a completely new team that will provide support and resources for needs that are shared across the growth strategy and development team. The senior managing director will manage a team of four that is focused on data and communications, event support, grant writing support, and prospect research. The ideal candidate is exceptional at relationship building and is a strong manager and strategic thinker, and possesses the ability to identify opportunities and systematically prioritize issues to drive toward shared outcomes.     Location: Flexible, anywhere in the U.S., New York City preferred     To read the full job description and apply for this role: http://bit.ly/SMDSCC

Teach For America is looking for outstanding candidates for the Chief of Staff to Chief Executive Officer and Founder of Teach For America, Wendy Kopp. This is an amazing opportunity for someone with critical thinking skills, exceptional communication and relationship building skills and a strong interest in Teach For America‚Äôs mission.     Application deadline: May 31st     If you know great people who might be interested, please contact: Alyssa Casden, director of talent recruitment: Alyssa.Casden@teachforamerica.org.     --------------------------------------------------------------------------------    Teach For America Career Opportunities  Teach For America is the national corps of outstanding college graduates and professionals who commit two years to teach in public schools in the nation's lowest income communities and become lifelong leaders in expanding educational opportunity.  We seek talented individuals of all backgrounds, with a strong record of achievement in their professional areas, to join our staff and play a critical role in enabling us to reach our ambitious goals.  Visit www.teachforamerica.org/careers for a full list of open positions and more information.      Chief of Staff, Office of the Chief Executive Officer and Founder   (Location: NYC preferred)     Teach For America seeks a chief of staff to provide critical, high level support to the CEO and founder and help advance the organization's strategic priorities.  This individual manages the planning and operations of the National Board of directors and works frequently with the organization's senior leadership, Executive Directors of our regions, and staff across all functional areas of the organization to manage projects and provide strategic support. This position provides an unparalleled opportunity for individuals with superior critical thinking, organization, communication, and relationship-building skills to help the CEO maximize Teach For America's current impact and future growth while gaining an in-depth understanding of the organization's operations. Due to the high-stakes nature of this position, the chief of staff must demonstrate exceptional judgment, professionalism and poise at all times.
